review_blob: Beautiful red color, foggy as if unfiltered (yesss), thin creamy ring of head, aroma is malt and vanilla, palate is crisp and dry, flavor has just the right amount hop bitter to match the bready malts on this session ale, its crisp and refreshing... also in the flavor is vanilla? Why is there vanilla? It seems pretty distinct and well pronounced, Im pretty sure there actually is vanilla bean in this recipe, I dont think Im making it up... Its a good beer and I am really happy that this brewery exists
No head, beautiful bright red/orange, aroma is mild malt, great malt flavor without the malt sweetness and well bittered, super dry finish keeps me wanting to drink more n more, this is a great beer

black body with red highlights, no head, slightly sour aroma / chocolate malts, flavor is overpowered by sourness - maybe this is just a really old bottle? Theres no decipherable date stamp, so who knows... Ive got a feeling that this beer will be the cause of some gnarly gas tomorrow

foggy yellow, big rocky white head, nose is tart belg yeast, sweet maltose, belg tripel flavor... i understand that nobody in the us wants to fugg with brett in the brew house, but why claim "farmhouse ale"? Seems stupid to me, i mean i know a lot of breweries do this - to the point that i avoid "farmhouse ales" even though I actually love a real, true farmhouse ales. Out of respect for the style, I will slaughter all fake saisons.

Clear golden orange hue, fat lacy white head, mild citrus hop aroma, big fruity hop mouthful, slightly sweet and mildly syrupy - though not nearly as sticky and cloying as most IIPAs, big bitters. Im not a huge fan of the double IPAs in general, but this is the second time Ive picked up a bomber of this stuff, so that says something. Oh yah, and the label is real nice, love the botanical art.

Big rocky white head, clear caramel color, malty caramel flavor to match it, aroma is mostly malty, bitters on the back end of the sip, some cascade flavors but not overly floral, easy drinkin, one can always invites another
UPDATED: JAN 3, 2015
beer_name: Tri City Giant Slayer Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: This is pretty much exactly what I wanted it to be, light and refreshing, big hop flavor - yet not over bittered, just a damn good hop session, I wish there were more pale ales with this much hop flavor
Deep black body, thin ring of creamy brown head, mild roast nose, super thick mouthfeel, like drinking a milkshake, sweet residual sugars, dark chocolate finish, alcohol very present in flavor

Sweet malty nose, big malty flavor with floral hops and lingering ginger long after the sips been swallowed, hop bitters cut straight through this malt bomb, smoked malt flavor is very subtle - which is much preferable to the alterntive. This is a great easy drinkin ale, though way hoppier than a Scottish ale should be, and the ginger makes it one that youll likely stop drinking after a pint and move on to something with a little less going on

Clear golden amber color, light lacey white head, hop nose like youre smelling a bag of pellets before brewing, sort of tastes like that too, presumably because theres not really any malt to back em up, crisp bitters, interesting beer, I actually tried brewing something like this a few years ago and was not as success though this has some of the same characteristics that I didnt like ie very thin palate and hop bitters is like drinking cold carbonated hop tea.

Honey color, no head, thin body and dry, slight n strange medicinal flavors, bitter plastics (sulfur?), not the best cider Ive had on this trip, though I do appreciate its dry finish and lack of sugar. Bought this in Cashel, Ireland.

Brown darkness with some red highlights that allows light to pass through, thin ring of a head. Chocolate nose, toasty malt flavor that cracks into a dry finish, flavors of chocolate, well balanced bitters without any stand out hop flavors, maybe some mild Golding pine notes- but thats a reach. Very decent stout, much bigger flavor profile than the Guinness pints Ive been throwing back on this trip (which have also been really hitting the spot)
Clear golden hur, no head, a bit sweet, pale malt flavor, mild hop spice. Bought this at a bottle shop in cobh

Smells like rubbery columbusish hops as soon as I open the bottle, pours clear amber with a frothy cream colored head, flavor is toasty malt and well bittered hop presence, I honestly dont know the flavor of heather all too well, but the beer is delicious. I live in Seattle and drink IPAs all the time, theyre often sweet and syrupy and leave me feeling immediately dehydrated, this is crisp clean and refreshing - though, note this beer is only 5.2 % which would be considered a pale ale in America. Purchased in cobh Ireland.

Clear golden body, lacey white head, aroma is rubbery columbus hops that almost go toward a bretty funk nose, nice big bold bitters that arent at all gross and grassy, not a lot of fruity hop flavor (not enough by todays standards), a lot of cascade characters to the hop flavor profile - but not nearly t the degree we typically see from Sierra Nevada. A nice dub IPA, but nothing hot. 

I almost died a few days ago - seriously. I am very thankful to alive and able to drink this beer right now, bless.

Thin white head, clear deep brown body, nutty brown  sugar sweet malt nose, flavor is initially malty sweetness and then the bitter dry finish with some mild roast and big mouthfeel just finishes it right up. Is it just me, or has Sierra Nevada really stepped up their game in terms of new beers in the recent history?
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Tumbler Autumn Brown Ale

review_blob: Despite the label shown, I had this in a bottle, golden body, lacy white head, aroma of sweet malts and spicy hops, refreshing ale with a nice rigid bitter backbone, no hop flavor to speak of aside from a mild spice, malt forward ale, refreshing and straight to the point

I can tell as Im pouring it thats its on the flat side, very low carbonation, brown/black body no head at all, aroma is rich malt, dark roast, vanilla. Flavor is sweet and smooth, not very aggressive at all, the 8% is well hidden, quite a it of hop flavor in there too, I cant tell which varieties but it seems somewhat sticky, lots of chocolate in the flavor as well, I could really use a little more carbonation though, this is pretty much as flat as the day it came out the fermentor! Good flavors though

Intricate lacing, clear gold color, strange ale to filter, nice belgian yeast nose, flavor is mostly belgian yeast, finish is alcohol and bitters, sort of like a belgian single/triple with extra hops on the bittering end, good stuff but far less hoppy than other belgian IPAs Ive had, and what hops are there arent outwardly "american", none of the the big citrus bitters (amarillo, centennial, cascade, chinook, columbus, etc.) that alot of the west coasters throw into these Belgian IPAs... Good ale though!

deep dense brown color, roasty swet malt nose, flavor is chocolate, very very slight smoke, tobacco sorts of flavors, black tea, nice bitter backbone, dry finish, not  malt bomb by any means, good stuff.

Bottle from city beers, clear orange copper color, thin almost no white head, aroma is buttery caramel aka diacetyl, flavor is buttery caramel and a bitter backbone, no real substantial hop flavor, there are some faint hints at west coast citrus rind hops in the background, I probably got an old bottle and this is more of what I imagine a British twist on the IIPA might taste like, thats what theyre into on the East Coast right? Probably won;t buy it again but its not bad stuff at all if diacetyl doesnt ruin a beer for you.

Black body, creamy an head, aroma is mocha chocolate coffee with some fresh west coast hops, flavor is big malts, thick caramel, chucks of chocolate, some deep roast, a wide hop flavor and a hint of smoke, an amazing ale, one of the best beers Ive had in a long time, really great stuff!

Clear yellow body, thin white fiz, aroma is palisade dry hop, derf, flavor is one dimensional malt (said it was 100% 2Row at the brewery) and thin hop flavor of the palisade, which is sort of like a cross between cascade and centennial in flavor profile to me, smells a bit like amarillo too, good stuff! I love a single hop beer but Id like some variety in the grain bill.
beer_name: Triple Rock Single Hop Experience Palisade

review_blob: Big tan head, clear brown body, aroma is clean hop fruit, flavor is rich malts and huge bitters, much more roasted than I expected, chocolatey and hoppy, quite interesting and very aggresive, some hot alcohols burn the throat as well, not an easy drinking beer but an experience, well worth your $4 even if you are jobless

I wasnt expecting much out of this because of its wide distribution and the tendency for the hops to drop out of these things if they dont move through any stage of the distribution process quick enough, and I have to say that Im pleasantly surprised. Clear golden orange with no head, the aroma is bright and full of sticky icky hop cones, aromas of chinook grapefruit, flavor is citrus hop rind, the chinooks really dominate the flavor and aroma. Very nice affordable IPA here... from a brewery thats working pretty hard to be responsible in its environmental practices none the less.

clear slightly pale water with bubbles and a thin layer of white fiz, wonderful fresh floral spicey hop nose, flavor is direct and clean, slight hop spice flabor cuts through with a very nice balance of bitter to malt ration and dry at the end, great refresher for a hot east bay night

No head, copper amber body, aroma is sweet rich barley with hints of strawberries, flavor is mostly barley malt, caramel, strong flavor of barley balanced well with hop bitters, not hop forward though the malts take center stage, far different than any other IPA made in the region, definitely brit styled

Clear amber body, fluffy tan head, aroma is rich barley and soft floral hops, flavor is deep caramel, upfront bitters without much hop flavor, bitters all the way through to the end of this swig, finishes dry, I think this is a great example of an american strong ale one of the best Ive had in a while.

Tap at Cornucopia Downtown in Eugene, Black body, thin brown head, aroma is dark roasts and rich coffee, flavor is dark chocolate, mildly chalky, mild sweetness but really pretty dry, big thick body - filling stout texture, rich coffee bean, doesnt taste like enough to caffeinate you (try Bells Java stout) but enough to taste, good stout and it did its job after a bike ride out in the rain
Black body, thin head, aroma is mild smoke and roast, flavor is piney grass bitters with a tad of chocolate and smidgen of smoked malts, well bittered but could use a boost of hp flavor
Black body, flavor is chocolatey not roasty, mild hop dankness, piney hop freshness, tasty and refreshing, dry and bitter

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Golden body with a light white lace, aroma is caramel malts and cheesy hops... this might be an old bottle... flavor is big sweet malt, some hot alcohol, pungent hop bitters that seem a bit stale, possibly aged a little too long, cheesy centennial warrior juice, heavy body

Tall creamy off white head, clear amber body, aroma is distinctly sweet and fruity apple juice, caramel, mild roast, maybe a hint of tobacco, flavor is bold, initial flavor is all malt, caramel, mild rye spice, husk, mild roast, leads into dark fruit, raisins, figs, huge malt flavors are balanced very well against some piney noble hop bitters, mild diacetyl, tasty stuff! Extremely well balanced
Aroma is muted citrus hops and mild roast, black body with a tan head, flavor is grapefruit hops, juicy bitters and some mild chocolatey roast, good stuff
beer_name: Stone Sublimely Self Righteous Black IPA

review_blob: Draft: Chocolate nose, dark roasted malts, hints of belgian yeast type flavors, mild bitters, piney noble hop flavors, more chocolate, thin mouthfeel
CASK, they tapped the bung the same day I was drinking this, big frothy tan head, red amber coloring, aroma is some columbus and amarillo, flavor is columbus, body is thin and firkin-ish. Good stuff!

Amber brown color with no head, crystal clear, aroma is sweet barley, flavor is sweet barley... sort of bland and one dimensional, not a stand out... I really thought that a beer called chronic would have a big upfront columbus nose. False advertising if you ask me. It was a disappointment but it is a clean ale that is well balanced, just a little bland.
beer_name: Pizza Port Carlsbad Chronic Amber Ale (-2011)

review_blob: Aroma is amarillo with a hint at the belgian esters, flavor is mostly all sticky amarillo citrus hop flavors balanced with some residual malt sweetness and belgian yeast flavors, the beer is really heavy, I think that must be coming from the residuals... beautiful beer though, it was my favorite beer of the day at the carlsbad location

Aroma is basement funk, really old and rustic nose, color is foggy unfiltered gold with light lace, flavor is funk and added spices, black pepper really stands out in the flavor, body is light and the finish is super dry, the brett obviously had plenty of time to chew this guy down to 1. Interesting saison, i would recommend it to anyone who can appreciate a wild ale.

DRAFT HAND PUMP: Creamy white nitro head, clear orange body, flat low-carbonation body, caramel butterscotch flavor, mild ester fruitiness, evenly dispersed hop bitters, balanced, a bit thin due to the low carbonation and thin malt body, could use a little more hop edge and dryness to make this a thirst quencher

Looks thin for an impy stout, deep brown/black but it lets light through for some ruby highlights, no head, aroma is alcohol, sweet malt and deep roast,  flavor is mild oak, roast, hint of chocolate, pretty mild in general, extremely weak for an imperial stout

Pours crystal clear orange/red color, not brown at all, nose is all citrus hops, centennial and cascade, flavor is all tropical fruit hops, its true that the west coast style brown ales can be pretty hop forward... but theyre still brown!! This is not a brown ale, its an IPA. There is no roast at all in here, no chocolate, no nut, no brown color... a good ale that is quite tasty but a complete failure of a double brown (add SOME roast... please). I have to rate this as a double brown (would have rated it higher as an IPA) because Im looking at the bottle and thats whats printed on it.

Clear ruby orange color with no head, aroma is sweet malt, barley, flavor is english/scottish yeast and sweet barley malt, super malty but well balanced with strong bitters, very much like a scottish we heavy, dark fruit esters, dry finish, tasty

Deep Brown/black body, thin tan head, aroma is pretty much spot on Peanut Butter and Jelly, really smells like Im about to gobble down a PB&J; (maybe i need a glass of milk with this beer) flavor misses the mark for the samich, tart acidic berry flavor that pushes through to the finish, a hint at peanut but not much there in terms of the peanut butter cant really taste any, mild roast, chalky black malt, an interesting ale, definitely drinkable and worth a try, I applaud the effort, must be a homebrewer in charge over at Shorts

Blend 2, 2009: Strong tall head, ruby brown body unfiltered, aroma is strong brett stank mild acid and a hint at where there once was a malt body, flavor is brett, bitter hop layers without hop flavor, citrus sour tart, mild acid, more sour than I had expected but by no means on the level of geuese, sharp bitters and edgy sours, pilsener malt flavors stand out as well, brett dominated strong ale, very very funky

aroma is some mild roast, alcohol and very faint peanut butter, appearance is black with a thin brown head, sweet flavor, chocolate, alcohol, dry charcoal black malt, roast, mild peanut on the finish, cream, interesting but some really hot alcohol flavors, fusel alcohol, I really appreciate the attempt to make a weird stout, totally home brew style recipe and that is a beautiful thing, points added for exhibitionism

First of all, is this really 9%?!? Honestly tastes like 6% TOPS, I really dont believe this could be 9, well, keep a six pack around for your date if nothing else! 

Clear ruby cranberry color with a very light white head, I can tell its not filtered despite the clarity of this sauce, aroma is pilsener malt and raspberry, flavor is light pilsener malt, edgy bitters and some extra bitter tannin kick too, mildly tart and slightly acidic, this stuff is really a lot better much warmer than your fridge temp. so that more of the interesting fruit flavors can come through, a little grassy

unfiltered orange body with a nice long lasting thin white head that laces up a little bit, aroma is hops but some caramel malt fits through ad well, flavor is cascade hops that is balanced very well with a strong malt backbone, after reading a few other reviews I think my bottle might be a little old as its really lacking the bright hop flavor that we get from say Pliney and Hop Stoopid, I can tell it must have been amazing fresh out of the fermentor, but it remains a well balanced treat even after the flavor/aroma hop additions start to fade... still this really cant even compare to many west coast DIPAs that are rated waaaay below this

Clear Filtered body, amber, thin white head, mild lace, aroma is toffee malts, rye spice and mild hop spice, flavor is big and bold, heavy handed bitter addition backs up the rye spice for a huge flavor punch, refreshing. Bold roast, much roastier than others in this style, almost an american brown ale in terms of flavor. Im really enjoying this ale, best Ive had from Flying Dog
